    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="span">Dictionary.com gives a very important and interesting everyday meaning of intuitive as being derived from or prompted by a natural tendency;</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> 
&quot;an intuitive perception&quot;.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="37" relname="span"> 
The key words here are DERIVED and NATURAL TENDENCY.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="36" relname="span"> 
This means that the task should be naturally and correctly carried out from the onset,</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="4" relname="otherwise">
otherwise it is never intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="12" relname="span"> 
I particularly liked the scenarios described by Raskin, J in his paper Intuitive equals familiar (an interesting paper).</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="preparation"> 
Here they are; </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="7" relname="list">

1) Stephen Oppenheimer, of the Review Board of InfoWorld magazine, noted in his review of Mathcad 4.0 that &quot;The editing tools become increasingly intuitive over time.&quot; </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="7" relname="list">

2) Richard Collins in Flying (October 1994 pg. 67), speaking of a new aircraft navigation device, 
&quot;Like anything, it can be learned, but it would take a lot of experience to do it intuitively.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="35" relname="span"> 
The point here is that there is nothing like increasingly becoming intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="34" relname="span"> 
We could roughly equate intuitive with what we call common sense .</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="33" relname="span"> 
We often hear people saying; COMMON SENSE SHOULD HAVE TOLD YOU THAT </segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="30" relname="evidence">
Since the person didnt naturally do the task right the very first time, </segment>
    <segment id="30" parent="32" relname="span">
therefore (to him/her) it ceased being common sense. 

</segment>
